{"rating": 3.7, "genres": ["Documentary"], "review": "This was a good documentary that has some very interesting parts to it.br br The problem is there are way too many bad parts in this movie for me to give it more than two stars. It seems like they could have used a better editor because it feels choppy at times. There are also a lot of things missing from the film. For instance, we never learn what happens after the participants go through Blackout. We see them sign their consent forms and then we don't see them again until they appear on screen as interviewed subjects. Why did they decide not to follow up with these people after they went through Blackout? What happened afterwards? Were any of the people harmed or traumatized by this experience? These questions aren't addressed and I think it would have been great if they had been.br br Another thing I didn't care for were the interviewees who just weren't convincing. They all seemed like they knew they were being filmed and that they were supposed to say something but I couldn't get behind anything they said.br br I enjoyed seeing the first part of the documentary where the crew goes through Blackout and meets some of the participants. After that though it gets really boring. The interviews don't make it worthwhile.br br Overall I thought the concept was interesting but the execution wasn't."}

What you actually get is a film with no plot or character development. There are hints of potential, like an isolated cabin in the woods and the promise of something bad lurking within, but they never develop beyond the surface level.br br The main characters, who seem to have been plucked straight out of a fraternity party, spend most of the movie drinking beer, getting drunk, and talking about the possibility that something evil exists in the woods. A couple of them actually do venture into the woods and wander around aimlessly for awhile, but then return to the cabin without having learned anything.br br At one point, there is a reference to a legend involving the fountain, which makes sense since it is supposed to be based on Native American mythology. However, it doesn't appear anywhere in the actual movie, so why bother mentioning it? Why not just set the story somewhere completely unrelated to its original inspiration?br br There is one scene near the end of the movie that is mildly creepy. However, after watching it, you wonder why anyone would want to revisit the location. After seeing the horrible conditions in the cabin, the broken windows, the trash strewn everywhere, the rotting food and the lack of running water, you wouldn't want to go back there either."}
